SIMPLE: trap
RECORDS: 6

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Trap
<hw>Trap</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Trapped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Trapping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Akin to OE. <ets>trappe</ets>
trappings, and perhaps from an Old French word of the same origin as E.
<ets>drab</ets> a kind of cloth.]</ety> <def>To dress with ornaments; to
adorn; -- said especially of horses.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Steeds . . . that <qex>trapped</qex> were in steel all
glittering.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To deck his hearse, and <qex>trap</qex> his tomb-black steed.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There she found her palfrey <qex>trapped</qex>⟦br⟧
In purple blazoned with armorial gold.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trap</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Trap
<hw>Trap</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sw. <ets>trapp</ets>; akin to
<ets>trappa</ets> stairs, Dan. <ets>trappe</ets>, G. <ets>treppe</ets>,
D. <ets>trap</ets>; -- so called because the rocks of this class often
occur in large, tabular masses, rising above one another, like steps.
See <er>Tramp</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>An old term rather
loosely used to designate various dark-colored, heavy igneous rocks,
including especially the feldspathic-augitic rocks, basalt, dolerite,
amygdaloid, etc., but including also some kinds of diorite. Called also
<altname>trap rock</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Trap tufa</b></col>, <col><b>Trap
tuff</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a kind of fragmental rock made up of
fragments and earthy materials from trap rocks.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trap</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Trap
<hw>Trap</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to trap rock; <as>as,
a <ex>trap</ex> dike</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trap</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Trap
<hw>Trap</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>trappe</ets>, AS.
<ets>treppe</ets>; akin to OD. <ets>trappe</ets>, OHG. <ets>trapo</ets>;
probably fr. the root of E. <ets>tramp</ets>, as that which is trod
upon: cf. F. <ets>trappe</ets>, which is trod upon: cf. F.
<ets>trappe</ets>, which perhaps influenced the English word.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A machine or contrivance that shuts suddenly, as with a
spring, used for taking game or other animals; <as>as, a <ex>trap</ex>
for foxes</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She would weep if that she saw a mouse⟦br⟧
Caught in a <qex>trap</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: A snare; an ambush; a stratagem; any device by
which one may be caught unawares.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let their table be made a snare and a <qex>trap</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Rom. xi. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God and your majesty⟦br⟧
Protect mine innocence, or I fall into⟦br⟧
The <qex>trap</qex> is laid for me!</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A wooden instrument shaped somewhat like a shoe,
used in the game of trapball. It consists of a pivoted arm on one end of
which is placed the ball to be thrown into the air by striking the other
end. Also, a machine for throwing into the air glass balls, clay
pigeons, etc., to be shot at.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The game of trapball.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A bend, sag, or partitioned chamber, in a drain,
soil pipe, sewer, etc., arranged so that the liquid contents form a seal
which prevents passage of air or gas, but permits the flow of
liquids.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A place in a water pipe, pump, etc., where air
accumulates for want of an outlet.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A wagon, or other vehicle.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>A kind of movable stepladder.</def>
<rj><au>Knight.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Trap stairs</b></col>, <cd>a staircase leading to a
trapdoor.</cd> -- <col><b>Trap tree</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <cd>the
jack; -- so called because it furnishes a kind of birdlime. See 1st
<er>Jack</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trap</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Trap
<hw>Trap</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>treppan</ets>. See <er>Trap</er> a snare.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To catch in a trap or traps; <as>as, to
<ex>trap</ex> foxes</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: To insnare; to take by stratagem; to
entrap.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧I <xex>trapped</xex> the foe.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To provide with a trap; <as>as, to <ex>trap</ex> a
drain; to <ex>trap</ex> a sewer pipe</as>. See 4th <er>Trap</er>,
5.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trap</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Trap
<hw>Trap</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To set traps for game; to make a
business of trapping game; <as>as, to <ex>trap</ex> for
beaver</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trapan</ent>⟦br⟧
